    <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к <mentioned xml:lang="x-oldirn"><lang/><w>axšaina</w></mentioned>.
        Старое иранское обозначение темно-серого или темно-синего цвета, частью вытесненное, частью
        существующее рядом с субстратным <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cʼæx"/> q. v. %iÆxsīn%i
        употребительно теперь преимущественно в Дигории и то не повсюду, но производное от него <ref
            type="xr" target="#entry_æxsīnæg"/> ‘голубь’ распространено по всей Осетии (ср.
            <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/><w>голубой</w></mentioned> и <mentioned xml:lang="ru"
                ><lang/><w>голубь</w></mentioned>, а также <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>kabūd</w><gloss><q>голубой</q></gloss></mentioned> и <mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kabūtar</w><gloss><q>голубь</q></gloss></mentioned>). Ос.
        %iæxsīn%i восходит непосредственно к <mentioned xml:lang="xsc"
            ><lang/><w>αξειν-</w></mentioned>, сохраненному древними авторами (Пиндар, Еврипид,
        Страбон) в названии Черного моря: Πόντος Άξεινος „темно-синий Понт“. Впоследствии греки
        переделали <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>ἄξεινος</w></mentioned>, осмыслявшееся ими
        как „негостеприимный“, в <mentioned xml:lang="grc"
        ><lang/><w>εύξεινος</w></mentioned>„гостеприимный“: <mentioned xml:lang="grc"
                ><lang/><w>Ποντος Εύξεινος</w></mentioned> (<bibl><ref
                target="#ref_Vasmer._Ir._i._S."/><biblScope>20</biblScope></bibl>). Помимо
        скифо-осетинского, слово широко представлено в других иранских языках: <mentioned
            xml:lang="ydg"><lang/><w>axšīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="yah"
                ><lang/><w>šīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="oru"
            ><lang/><w>ṣīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ps"><lang/><w>ṣīn</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="ku"><lang/><w>šīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
                ><lang/><w>xasīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="pal"
            ><lang/><w>axšēn</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="pal"><w>xašēn</w><note
                type="comment" xml:lang="ru">zray-i-Xašēn „Черное море“</note><note type="comment"
                xml:lang="en">zray-i-Xašēn "Black See"</note></mentioned>, :
                <bibl><author>Фрейман</author><ref target="#ref_ЗКВ"/><biblScope>V 647
                сл.</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>āṣṣeina</w></mentioned>
                (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Leumann"/><biblScope>397</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
            xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>*axšēn('γs'yn)</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="sog"
                ><w>*axšēnāk('γs'yn'k)</w></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="ae"
                ><lang/><w>axšaena-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="peo"
                ><lang/><w>axšaina-</w></mentioned> (<mentioned xml:lang="peo"><lang/><w>kasaka hya
                axšaina</w></mentioned> „синий самоцвет“ = ляпис-лазурь?). Этимологически
        %iaxšaina%i- разлагается на %ia%i-%ixšaina%i-, буквально „не-сияющий“; ср. для второй части
        ос. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_xsīd"/> | xsed ‘заря’. Ср. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_æxsīnæg"/> ‘голубь’.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>21, 38,
                158</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">It traces back to <mentioned xml:lang="x-oldirn"
            ><lang/><w>axšaina</w></mentioned>. It is an ancient Iranian notion of dark-grey and
        dark-blu colour, which is partially was forced out and which is partially existing near a
        substrate <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cʼæx"/> q. v. %iÆxsīn%i is common now in Digoria and
        not even everywhere but its derivative <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æxsīnæg"/> ‘pigeon’ is
        common all over Ossetia (cf. <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/><w>goluboj</w></mentioned> and
            <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/><w>golub'</w></mentioned>, and also <mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kabūd</w><gloss><q>blue</q></gloss></mentioned> and <mentioned
            xml:lang="fa"><lang/><w>kabūtar</w><gloss><q>pigeon</q></gloss></mentioned>). Ossetic
        word %iæxsīn%i traces back directly to <mentioned xml:lang="xsc"
            ><lang/><w>αξειν-</w></mentioned>, which was saved by ancient authors (Pindar,
        Euripides, Strabo) in the name of the Black Sea: %iΠόντος%i %iΆξεινος%i ‘dark-blue Pontus’.
        Later the Greeks remade <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>ἄξεινος</w></mentioned>, which
        was interpreted as ‘unwelcome’, into <mentioned xml:lang="grc"
            ><lang/><w>εύξεινος</w></mentioned>"welcome": <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>Ποντος
                Εύξεινος</w></mentioned> (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Vasmer._Ir._i._S."
                /><biblScope>20</biblScope></bibl>). Besides Scythian-Ossetic, the word is widely
        spread in other Iranian languages: <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"
        ><lang/><w>axšīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="yah"><lang/><w>šīn</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="oru"><lang/><w>ṣīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ps"
                ><lang/><w>ṣīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ku"
            ><lang/><w>šīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"
        ><lang/><w>xasīn</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="pal"
            ><lang/><w>axšēn</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="pal"><w>xašēn</w><note
                type="comment" xml:lang="ru"> (zray-i-Xašēn ‘Черное море’)</note><note
                type="comment" xml:lang="en"> (zray-i-Xašēn ‘Black Sea’)</note></mentioned>, :
                (<bibl><author>Фрейман</author><ref target="#ref_ЗКВ"/><biblScope>V 647
                сл.</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned xml:lang="kho"><lang/><w>āṣṣeina</w></mentioned>
                (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Leumann"/><biblScope>397</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
            xml:lang="sog"><lang/><w>*axšēn('γs'yn)</w></mentioned><mentioned xml:lang="sog"
                ><w>*axšēnāk('γs'yn'k)</w></mentioned>, , <mentioned xml:lang="ae"
                ><lang/><w>axšaena-</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="peo"
                ><lang/><w>axšaina-</w></mentioned> (<mentioned xml:lang="peo"><lang/><w>kasaka hya
                axšaina</w></mentioned> "blue gem" = lapis lazuli?). According to ethymology,
        %iaxšaina%i- is derived from %ia%i-%ixšaina%i-, literally ‘not-shining’; cf. for the second
        part Ossetic <ref type="xr" target="#entry_xsīd"/> | %ixsed%i ‘dawn’. Cf. <ref type="xr"
            target="#entry_æxsīnæg"/> ‘pigeon’.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>21, 38,
                158</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
